# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc-two
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:bbc-two/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:bbc-two/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:bbc-two/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:bbc-two/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:bbc-two/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] The **1967 Wimbledon Championships** took place on the outdoor grass courts at the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club in Wimbledon, London, United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] The tournament was held from Monday 26 June until Saturday 8 July 1967.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] It was the 81st staging of the Wimbledon Championships, and the third Grand Slam tennis event of 1967.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] John Newcombe and Billie Jean King won the singles titles.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] The first colour television broadcast in the UK, as well as in Europe, took place on 1 July 1967, the first Saturday of the Championships, when, starting at 2 pm, four hours of live coverage of the Championships was shown on BBC2 presented by David Vine and with commentary from Keith Fordyce.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] The first match broadcast in colour was Cliff Drysdale against Roger Taylor and was played on the Centre Court.
[src:bbc-two/1967-wimbledon-championships] Additional colour broadcasts were made during the afternoons of the following week as well as 30-minute highlight programmes shown each evening.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Bauer is portrayed as a highly proficient agent with an "ends justify the means" approach, willing to lie, threaten, or even harm anyone who refuses to cooperate with him.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Throughout the series, the plot elements contain both a political thriller and serial drama, with each episode typically ending on a cliffhanger.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Bauer uses people on both sides of the law in his attempts to prevent terrorist attacks and bring down those responsible, sometimes at great personal expense.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] These attacks include presidential assassination attempts, bomb detonations, bioterrorism and cyberwarfare, as well as conspiracies that involve government and corporate corruption.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In addition to Bauer, each episode typically follows other American government officials from CTU/FBI/CIA and the White House, as well as the conspirators who set the events in motion.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Because many of these conspirators commit murder for political gain, several of Bauer's contacts are killed as a consequence of government intervention.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The grief that Bauer experiences from these deaths is often explored throughout the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] While Bauer does have the utmost respect for most of his colleagues, friends and family members, he always believes himself to know how to provide the best way of saving innocent lives and/or achieving his own sense of justice, often being proven right when taking action.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 1 begins at midnight on the day of the California presidential primary in Los Angeles.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 2, set 18 months later, begins at 8:00 a.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack must stop a nuclear bomb from detonating in Los Angeles, then assist the now-President Palmer in proving who is responsible for the threat and avoid war between the U.S. and three Middle Eastern countries.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 3, set three years later, begins at 1:00 p.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack must infiltrate a Mexican drug cartel led by Ramon and Hector Salazar, to seize a deadly virus being marketed underground.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] President Palmer must deal with a potential scandal that could cost him his presidency.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 4, set 18 months later, begins at 7:00 a.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack must save the lives of his new boss, United States Secretary of Defense James Heller, who Jack now works for as a special assistant, and Heller's daughter Audrey Raines (with whom Jack is romantically involved) when they are kidnapped by terrorists.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] However, Turkish terrorist mastermind Habib Marwan uses this as a disguise to launch further attacks against America, and Jack is forced to use unorthodox methods to stop him, which results in long-term consequences for both Jack and the United States.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 5, set 18 months after, begins at 7:00 a.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack is believed to be dead by everyone except a few of his closest friends.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] He is forced to resurface when some of those friends are assassinated and he is framed by terrorists with connections to the U.S. government.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The acquisition of nerve gas by the terrorists poses a new threat, and Jack discovers an insidious conspiracy while trying to stop those responsible.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 6, set 20 months later, begins at 6:00 a.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack is released after being captured by Chinese official Cheng Zhi and being detained in a Chinese prison following the events of Season 5.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Terrorists led by Abu Fayed who hold a vendetta against Jack plot to set off suitcase nuclear devices in America.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Later, Jack is forced to choose between those he loves and national security when the Chinese set their sights on sensitive circuitry that could trigger a war between the U.S. and Russia.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 7, set 65 days after the end of *Redemption*, begins at 8:00 a.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] CTU is disbanded, and Jack is assisted by the FBI and covert operatives when the firewall for America's federal computer infrastructure is breached by the same people responsible for a conflict in Sangala.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack must uncover corruption within the now-President Taylor's administration, which has allowed the Sangalans to raid the White House and capture Taylor.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] She is later blackmailed by Starkwood, a fictional private military company led by its CEO, Jonas Hodges, in an attempt to release biological weapons on U.S. soil.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Season 8, set 18 months later, begins at 4:00 p.m.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack is brought in by the now-reinstated CTU to uncover a Russian plot to assassinate Middle Eastern leader Omar Hassan, the President of the fictional country of the Islamic Republic of Kamistan, during peace negotiations with President Taylor at the United Nations in New York City.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Russia's contingency plan involves engineering a dirty bomb, which Islamic extremists threaten to detonate in Manhattan unless Hassan is handed over.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack later seeks retribution for personal losses suffered, including the death of ex-FBI Special Agent Renee Walker, after former President Charles Logan convinces Taylor to cover up these crimes to protect the peace agreement.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jack finds himself at odds with both the Russian and U.S. governments.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The idea for the series first came from executive producer Joel Surnow, who initially had the idea of a TV show with 24 episodes in a season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Each episode would be an hour long, taking place over the course of a single day.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] He discussed the idea over the phone with producer Robert Cochran, whose initial response was "Forget it, that's the worst idea I've ever heard, it will never work and it's too hard".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] They met the next day at the International House of Pancakes in Woodland Hills, Los Angeles, to discuss the idea of this action-espionage series that used the format of real time to create dramatic tension with a race against the clock.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The pilot for *24* was pitched to Fox who immediately bought it, saying they felt that the idea for the series was one that would "move the form of television forward".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The episode had a $4 million budget with filming in March 2001.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The set of CTU was initially done in a Fox Sports office, with the set reproduced once the series was picked up for the season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series was supposed to be filmed in Toronto, but due to the variability of Canadian weather, Los Angeles was chosen as a filming location.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The pilot of the series was well received by critics, and was signed on for an initial thirteen episodes.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Production began in July 2001, and the premiere was planned for October 30, but because of the September 11 attacks, delayed until November 6.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] After the first three episodes, Fox greenlit the remaining filmed 11 episodes and following Kiefer Sutherland's Golden Globe win, Fox ordered the second half of the season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Although not the first to do so, *24* embraced the concept of real time.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] This idea started when producer Joel Surnow thought of the idea of doing "24 episodes in a season, with each episode lasting an hour".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] They decided that the idea of real time had to make the show a "race against the clock".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Each episode takes place over the course of one hour, with time continuing to elapse during the commercial breaks.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The exact time is denoted by the digital clock display at the beginning and end of each segment.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The protocol is that mundane events, such as travel, sometimes occur during commercial breaks and thus these events are largely unseen.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The story time correlates with elapsed viewing time if episodes are broadcast with commercial breaks of set duration inserted at the points prescribed by the episode.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In line with the depiction of events in real time, *24* does not use slow motion techniques.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series also does not use flashbacks, except once during the first-season finale.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Watched continuously without advertisements, each season would run approximately 17 hours.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] As a result of the timing nature of the series, a number of visual cues were projected onto the screen.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Another idea was the use of split screens, which was born out of the number of phone calls there were, and because of the element of real time, was used to trace parallel adventures of different characters, and aid in the connecting of characters.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was used by producers to point the audience to where to pay attention, as secondary stories often take place outside of the main plot.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The idea of using boxes came later, which made shooting more flexible, as the shot could be cropped and reshaped inside the box.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was from here that the idea of using split screens as an artistic element came into the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] A major concept used in the series was the idea of a running clock.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] This initially came from Joel Surnow, who wanted the audience to always know what time it was in the show's fictional timeline.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] This was done by an on-screen digital clock that appears before and after commercial breaks, and a smaller clock also appears at other points in the narrative.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The time shown is the in-universe time of the story.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] When the running clock is shown full screen, an alternating pulsating beeping noise (like the kind seen on a time bomb) for each second can usually be heard.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] On rare occasions, a silent clock is used.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] This usually follows the death of a major character or an otherwise dramatic event.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The first six seasons of the show are mostly based in Los Angeles and nearby California locations—both real and fictional.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Other locations, such as Washington, D.C., are featured in parts of the fourth, sixth, and seventh seasons.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The eighth season takes place in New York City, the TV film *Redemption*, filmed in South Africa, is mainly set in the fictional African nation of Sangala, and the ninth season *Live Another Day* is set in London.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The main setting of the show is the fictional Counter Terrorist Unit.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Its office consists of two main departments: Field Operations, which involves confronting and apprehending suspects, and Communications, which gathers intelligence and assists those that work in Field Operations.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] CTU offices are established in various cities with these units reporting to "Divisions", and Divisions reporting to the "District".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] While CTU itself is a fictional agency, several entities with similar names or duties, like the National Counterterrorism Center, have emerged since the show's debut on television.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The set of CTU was initially filmed in a Fox Sports office, with the set recreated in a studio in Woodland Hills after the series was picked up.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The same set was used for the first three seasons, but production moved to an old pencil factory in Chatsworth before the start of the fourth season and the CTU set was redesigned.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was redesigned again before the start of the eighth season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Other sets were also constructed here, such as Charles Logan's presidential retreat shown in seasons five and six, and the White House bunker shown in seasons four and six.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] On March 26, 2010, a statement was issued from Fox that explained that season eight would conclude the original series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Executive producer and showrunner Howard Gordon was also a part of the decision.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It's truly been an amazing and unforgettable eight days.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The final episode of season 8 aired on May 24, 2010.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Immediately prior to *24*, series co-creators Joel Surnow and Robert Cochran executive-produced *La Femme Nikita* for its entire five-year run on USA Network.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Both series deal with anti-terrorist operations, and the lead characters of both series are placed in situations in which they must make a tragic choice in order to serve the greater good.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] There are numerous on- and off-screen creative connections between *24* and *La Femme Nikita*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Several actors from *La Femme Nikita* have portrayed similar roles on *24*, a number of story concepts from *La Femme Nikita* have been revisited on *24*, and many of the creative personnel from *La Femme Nikita* worked on *24* in their same role.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Similar to the 1997 film, *Air Force One*, *24* featured the president's personal jumbo-jet (Air Force One).
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Air Force One was featured in *24* seasons 2 and 4.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Air Force Two (carrying the Vice President but not the President) was featured in season 6.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Several actors featured in *24*, such as Xander Berkeley, Glenn Morshower, Wendy Crewson, Timothy Carhart, Jürgen Prochnow, Tom Everett and Spencer Garrett also appeared in the film *Air Force One*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The 25th amendment, which deals with succession to the Presidency and establishes procedures for filling a vacancy in the office of the Vice President and responding to presidential disabilities, was also a shared theme between the film and the television series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] *24* used the same Air Force One set from another television series, *The West Wing*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] A feature film adaptation of *24* was originally planned for the hiatus between the sixth and seventh seasons.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Series co-creators Joel Surnow and Robert Cochran were set to write the script with showrunner Howard Gordon working on story.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Filming was going to take place in London, Prague, and Morocco.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Plans for the film were later put on hold.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was later decided that the film would begin after the conclusion of the eighth and final season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was to be set and shot on-location in Europe.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Surnow, Cochran, Gordon, and Sutherland were going to be executive producers on the film, and Billy Ray was going to write the screenplay.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Shooting was planned to start in late 2010 or early 2011.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In April 2010, Sutherland said in an interview at a BAFTA event in London that the script was finished and he would be reading it upon his return to the United States.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] He also said that the film will be a two-hour representation of a twenty-four-hour time frame.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In June 2010, it was reported that plans were made to create a film titled *Die Hard 24/7*, which would serve as a crossover between *24* and the *Die Hard* franchise, with Sutherland to reprise his role as Jack Bauer alongside Bruce Willis' John McClane.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] However, these plans never came to fruition, with the studio instead opting to create the film *A Good Day to Die Hard*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In November 2010, executive producer Gordon revealed that a "work in progress" screenplay was being read by Fox, but that the film did not yet have a green-light or fixed schedule.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In December 2010, Gordon revealed that Fox turned down the script by Ray, stating, "It wasn't strong enough or compelling enough".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] By that time, Gordon was no longer involved with the project, but stated that director Tony Scott would pitch an idea to Sutherland, an involvement ending with Scott's death in August 2012.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Executive producer Brian Grazer tweeted in April 2011 that the film was planned for a 2012 release.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] At the 2011 Television Critics Association press tour, former showrunner Gordon stated that "conversations are definitely happening" about the film, and that they are just looking for the right script before moving forward.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In September 2011, Sutherland indicated the script was almost complete.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] After some small script alterations by screenwriter Mark Bomback, filming was announced to begin in spring 2012, after Sutherland became available in April.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In March 2012, 20th Century Fox stopped production before filming could begin.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Budgetary issues remained unresolved and Sutherland's narrow time frame for filming were cited as reasons for halting production.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] However, in July 2012, Sutherland assured the film was still in plans and that they would begin filming in summer 2013.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The film was eventually suspended in May 2013 after the announcement that the show would return as a limited series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Sutherland said in January 2014 that "the film is an ongoing situation." After *Live Another Day* received highly positive reception, a new idea for the feature film surfaced in September 2014, spearheaded by Grazer.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In July 2024, it was reported that a *24* feature film was in early development at 20th Century Studios and Imagine Entertainment.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In November 2025, Imagine Entertainment president Justin Wilkes said there were plans to continue *24* with Jack Bauer by way of a theatrical film or follow-up television series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In May 2013, *Deadline Hollywood* first reported that Fox was considering a limited-run "event series" for *24* based on a concept by Howard Gordon, after failed efforts to produce the *24* feature film and the cancellation of Kiefer Sutherland's series *Touch*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The following week, Fox officially announced *24: Live Another Day*, a limited-run series of twelve episodes that would feature the return of Jack Bauer.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Fox CEO Kevin Reilly said that the series would essentially represent the twelve "most important" hours of a typical *24* season, with jumps forward between hours as needed.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In June 2013, it was announced that Jon Cassar was signed to executive produce and direct multiple episodes of *Live Another Day*, including the first two.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Executive producers and writers Robert Cochran, Manny Coto and Evan Katz were also announced to return with Sean Callery returning as the music composer for the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Mary Lynn Rajskub was announced as the second official cast member in August 2013, reprising her role as Chloe O'Brian.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In October 2013, it was confirmed that Kim Raver and William Devane would reprise their roles as Audrey Raines and James Heller, respectively.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In October 2013, it was confirmed the series would be set and filmed in London, England.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In January 2015, another installment of the franchise was pitched by executive producers Howard Gordon, Evan Katz, Manny Coto and Brian Grazer, which would revolve around a stable of supporting characters rather than Kiefer Sutherland in the lead role.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In January 2016, Fox announced it had ordered a pilot for a spin-off series titled *24: Legacy*, which would feature a new cast, with no returning characters except Tony Almeida (Carlos Bernard).
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series retains the real-time format, but consists of 12 episodes, using a time jump to cover a single day.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Stephen Hopkins, who directed the original *24* pilot and several first-season episodes, directed the *Legacy* pilot.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jon Cassar also returned to direct and produce 6 of the 12 episodes.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Corey Hawkins and Miranda Otto play the two lead characters – Hawkins as Eric Carter, a military hero returning home and Otto as Rebecca Ingram, a former head of CTU.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The pilot was officially ordered to series in April 2016 and premiered on February 5, 2017, immediately after Super Bowl LI.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In June 2017, the series was canceled after one season.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In July 2018, it was announced that Fox was in the early stages of developing a prequel series that would tell the origin story about Jack Bauer in his early days.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Original creators Joel Surnow and Robert Cochran and executive producer Howard Gordon were set to write the script with.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In August 2018, it was announced that Fox was also developing another potential spin-off, which would be a legal thriller.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In February 2019, Fox passed on the legal thriller, but were continuing to develop the prequel.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In January 2020, Fox confirmed that they had scrapped the potential prequel series as well.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In September 2021, *Deadline Hollywood* reported that Fox was in "active creative talks" to bring the franchise back in a new form.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] He later went on to tell *Variety* in April 2022 that he is open to new seasons of the show, as he views Jack Bauer's story as "unresolved".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] A significant amount of additional media relating to the series has been created, including Internet-distributed spin-off series such as *The Rookie* and *24: Conspiracy*, as well as a video game.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Other media include action figures of some of the main characters, soundtracks from both the series and the video game, and a number of novels covering different events not covered in the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Additionally, a number of in-universe books were created, as well as behind the scenes books containing information on how the series was created.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Throughout its run *24* was frequently cited by critics as one of the best shows on television.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Its fifth season was its most critically acclaimed season, scoring universally positive reviews from critics, with the last three seasons each receiving generally favorable reviews.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The production and quality of the series has been frequently called "filmlike" and better than most films.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series has been compared to old-fashioned film serials, like *The Perils of Pauline*.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The quality of the acting was particularly celebrated by critics.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Robert Bianco of *USA Today* described Kiefer Sutherland as indispensable to the series, and that he had a "great, under-sung performance".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Dennis Haysbert's "commanding" performance as David Palmer was hailed by critics, with some believing the character helped the campaign of Barack Obama.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] David Leonhart of *The New York Times* praised Gregory Itzin's portrayal of President Charles Logan, comparing his character to former U.S.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] *The New York Times* characterized Logan's administration as "a projection of our very worst fears" of the government.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jean Smart's portrayal of Martha Logan in the fifth season was equally acclaimed.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The character's opening scene (in which she, unsatisfied with her hairdo, dunks her head into a sink) was called "the most memorable character debut in *24* history".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The finale of season one is seen by many critics as one of the best episodes of the series and is frequently cited as one of the best television season finales of all time.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Teri Bauer's death at the end of the finale was voted by *TV Guide* as the second-most shocking death in television history.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Towards the middle of *24*'s run, the series attracted significant criticism for its depictions of torture, as well as its negative portrayal of Muslims.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In response to these concerns, members of the U.S. military met with the creators of the show.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Partly as a result of these discussions, and the military's appeal to the creators of the show to tone down the scenes of torture since it was having an impact on U.S. troops, there was a reduction in torture in subsequent seasons of the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] However, the writers stated that they reduced the number of torture scenes, not as a concession, but because it was starting to overwhelm the storytelling.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] He reportedly responded with a defense of Bauer, arguing that law enforcement officials deserve latitude in times of great crisis, and that no jury would convict Bauer in those types of situations.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The use of torture and the negative portrayal of Muslims affected the decisions of some actors who intended to join the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] However, she took on the role as she felt that people would understand that the show was fiction.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] During an interview for his new television series *Homeland*, *24* executive producer Howard Gordon addressed the impact of the series, describing it as "stunning – everyone from Rush Limbaugh to Bill Clinton would talk about it, and we knew they were among our fans.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] There were just certain things that we needed to portray in order to make it feel thrilling—and real, even.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] When discussing his regrets, he referred to an advertisement for the show for its fourth season (though mistakenly quoted it as an advertisement for the second season), saying "I actually do have regrets about one particular moment, which had more to do with the promotion of the show.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In season four, the story involved a Muslim American family, and the father and the mother—and the son—were party to a terror plot.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was sort of a purple conceit in a way.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] And I think our awareness of that changed the way we approached the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] After the series finale, the *Los Angeles Times* characterized the series as "an epic poem, with Jack Bauer in the role of Odysseus or Beowulf.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Seasonal rankings were based on average total viewers per episode of *24* on Fox.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Most American network television seasons start in mid-September and end in late May, which coincides with the completion of May sweeps.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] *24* aired during both February and May sweeps periods in all of its seasons, and during the November sweeps period in its first three seasons.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Beginning with its fourth season, *24* began its season in January and aired new episodes non-stop until May.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series was nominated for and won several other television awards including the Emmy Awards, Golden Globe Awards, and Screen Actors Guild Awards.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It is one of only five TV series (along with *NYPD Blue*, *The West Wing*, *Breaking Bad* and *Homeland*) ever to have won the Emmy Award, the Golden Globe and the Satellite Award for Best Drama Series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series received 68 Emmy nominations, with 20 wins.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It received nominations for Outstanding Drama Series at the Primetime Emmys in 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, and won the award in 2006.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Joel Surnow and Robert Cochran won for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series in 2002 for the pilot episode.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Composer Sean Callery received nine nominations for Outstanding Music Composition for a Series, nominated for every season and *24: Redemption*; he won in 2003, 2006, and 2010.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series' fifth season was its most successful for awards, earning twelve Emmy nominations and five wins, including Outstanding Drama Series and Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama for Sutherland (after being nominated every year previous).
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Jon Cassar won for Outstanding Directing in a Drama Series, and Itzin and Smart received Best Supporting Actor/Actress in a Drama Series nominations.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In 2009, Cherry Jones won for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series received twelve Golden Globe nominations with two wins.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It received nominations for Best Drama Series at the Golden Globes in 2001, 2002, 2004, and 2006, winning in 2003, and Kiefer Sutherland received nominations at the Golden Globes in 2002, 2003, 2005, 2006, and 2008 (for *24: Redemption*), winning in 2001.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] Dennis Haysbert received a nomination for Best Supporting Role in 2002.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series received ten Screen Actors Guild nominations with four wins.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] It was nominated for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series in 2003, 2005, and 2007 at the Screen Actors Guild Awards.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] The series won for Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a TV Series in 2008 and 2010.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In 2008, *Empire* magazine ranked *24* as the sixth-greatest television show of all time.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In 2013, the series was listed as #71 in the Writers Guild of America's list of the 101 Best Written TV Series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p01] In September 2019, *The Guardian* ranked the series 90th on its list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century, calling it "the most gripping TV drama of the 00s".
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] Fox's then-sister cable network FX aired a 24-hour marathon of the first season on September 1, 2002 (Labor Day).
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The release of *24* on DVD had a significant impact on the success of the television series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] In an interview with IGN in 2002, Sutherland revealed, "[*24'*s] success in [the UK] was phenomenal.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] It was the biggest show the BBC has ever had.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] It was the number one DVD there, knocking off *The Lord of the Rings*, which is unheard of for a television show DVD to actually knock-out every feature DVD available.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] And that's because they showed it without commercials." The American sales of the season one DVDs increased the audience size of season two by 25%.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] A special edition of the first season was released on May 20, 2008.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The new set includes a seventh disc of bonus features, while discs 1–6 contain all 24 episodes with deleted scenes, audio commentaries, and 5 extended episodes.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The television film *24: Redemption* was released on DVD in Region 1 on November 25, 2008, and in Region 2 on December 1, 2008.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The DVD contains the broadcast version as well as an extended version with optional audio commentary, a making-of featurette, child soldiers in Africa featurette, a season 6 recap, and the first 17 minutes of the season 7 premiere episode.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The seventh season was the first season to be released on Blu-ray format.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The eighth season, also on Blu-ray, was released simultaneously with the complete series set on DVD.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] On December 2, 2017, all eight seasons, *24: Redemption*, *24: Live Another Day* and *24: Legacy* were released on Blu-ray individually and in a box set by Fox Japan.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] All eight seasons and *24: Redemption* are available for purchase or rental on iTunes, Amazon Video on Demand, and previously the Zune Marketplace.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] *24* was available on Netflix in the United States, but was pulled from the service on April 1, 2014, and also pulled from the UK.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The show was pulled from Netflix Canada on January 1, 2018.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] In 2021, the series was added to streaming service Disney+ worldwide except for the United States where it is on Hulu, following the acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney in 2019.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] In Australia, *24: The Complete Series* was released on December 1, 2010, and was re-issued with a new designed box on November 2, 2016.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] In November 2011, Anil Kapoor purchased the rights to *24* to make an Indian adaptation of the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] Kapoor, who played Omar Hassan in season eight of the original series, plays the lead role in the adaptation that is based on Jack Bauer, and also produces the series.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] The series debuted in India on the television channel Colors on October 4, 2013.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] A 24-episode adaptation debuted in Japan on October 9, 2020, on the television channel TV Asahi.
[src:bbc-two/24-tv-series-p02] It stars Toshiaki Karasawa as CTU agent Genba Shidō.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] In August 2004, the London Development Agency (LDA) acquired 3 Mills Studios.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] As parent organisation of the *Creative London* agency, the LDA's role included supporting business and skills, researching industry needs, and promoting London for film-making.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] The site is now one of London's most important film and television studios.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] Ownership transferred to the London Legacy Development Corporation in 2010 which is the organisation responsible for planning, developing, and managing the Olympic Park after the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has over 75,000 sq ft (7,000 m2) of filming space, including 11 filming stages and nine rehearsal rooms.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] Stage 5 at 10,437 sq ft (969.6 m2) has a similar floor size to the Royal Albert Hall.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] There are nine rehearsal rooms on site: Rehearsal Room 6 at 2,507 sq ft (232.9 m2) is the largest and Rehearsal Room 3 at 280.9 sq ft (26.10 m2) is the smallest.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has a large range of ancillary spaces including; production offices, props workshops, five prop stores ranging from 712 to 1,319 sq ft (66.1 to 122.5 m2), make-up rooms, and dressing rooms.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] Many feature films have been made at 3 Mills Studios, including *Legend*, *Topsy-Turvy*, *Sexy Beast*, *Eastern Promises*, *Attack the Block*, *Berberian Sound Studio*, *Ill Manors*, *Powder Room*, *Made in Dagenham*, *Never Let Me Go*, *Farming* and *Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels*.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios' main focus has been on television shows.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has been home to BBC's *MasterChef* since 2014.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills was home to Channel 4's *Big Brother* for the first and second series along with the first series of *Celebrity Big Brother*.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] Other clients include Matthew Bourne's New Adventures, English National Opera, Raymond Gubbay Limited, Shakespeare's Globe and English National Ballet, as well as advertisers for Versace, Audi, Waitrose, Nissan, Gillette, Samsung, Gucci, Topshop, B&Q and Adidas.
[src:bbc-two/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios also housed many rehearsals for the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The **405-line** monochrome analogue television broadcasting system was the first fully electronic television system to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The number of television lines influences the image resolution, or quality of the picture.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] It was introduced with the BBC Television Service in 1936, suspended for the duration of World War II, and remained in operation in the UK until 1985.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] It was also used between 1961 and 1982 in Ireland, as well as from 1957 to 1973 for the Rediffusion Television cable service in Hong Kong.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] 405-line was approved as **System A** in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Sometimes called the **Marconi-EMI system**, it was developed in 1934 by the EMI Research Team led by Isaac Shoenberg.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The figure of 405 lines had been chosen following discussions over Sunday lunch at the home of Alan Blumlein.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The system used interlacing; EMI had been experimenting with a 243-line all-electronic interlaced system since 1933.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In the 405 system the scanning lines were broadcast in two complementary fields, 50 times per second, creating 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The actual image was 376 lines high and interlaced, with additional unused lines making the frame up to 405 lines to give the slow circuitry time to prepare for the next frame; in modern terms it would be described as *"376i"*.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] At the time of its introduction the 405-line system was referred to as *"high definition"* – which it was, compared to earlier systems, although of lower definition than 625-line and later standards.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In the United States, the FCC had briefly approved a 405-line color television standard in October 1950, which was developed by CBS.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The CBS system was incompatible with existing black-and-white receivers.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] It used a rotating color wheel, reduced the number of scan lines from 525 to 405, and increased the field rate from 60 to 144, but had an effective frame rate of only 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In 1934, the British government set up a committee (the "Television Committee") to advise on the future of TV broadcasting.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The committee recommended that a "high definition" service (defined by them as being a system of 240 lines or more) should be run and established by the BBC.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The recommendation was accepted and tenders were sought from industry.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Two tenders were received: one from the Baird company offering a 240-line mechanical system, and the other from EMI offering a 405-line all-electronic one.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The Television Committee advised that they were unable to choose between the two systems and that both tenders should be accepted, the two systems to be run together for an experimental period.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This became the standard for all British TV broadcasts until the 1960s.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] It soon became apparent that television reception was also possible well outside the original intended service area.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In February 1938, engineers at the RCA Research Station, Riverhead, Long Island, New York, in the US, were able to receive the BBC signal 5,000 km (3,100 mi) away, due to the signal being "bounced" back to earth from the ionosphere.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] A few minutes of programming were recorded on 16mm movie film.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This is now considered to be the only surviving example of pre-war live British television.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The images recorded included two of the original three BBC announcers, Jasmine Bligh and (in a brief shot) Elizabeth Cowell, an excerpt from an unknown period costume drama, and the BBC's station identification transmitted at the beginning and end of the day's programmes.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The BBC temporarily ceased transmissions on 1 September 1939, the day of the German invasion of Poland, for the outbreak of World War II was imminent.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] After the BBC Television Service recommenced in 1946, distant reception reports were received from various parts of the world, including Italy, South Africa, India, the Middle East, North America and the Caribbean.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The BBC lost its monopoly of the British television market in 1954, and the following year the commercial network ITV, comprising a consortium of regional companies, was launched.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The subcarrier frequency was 2.6578125 MHz (525/2 times line frequency) with an "I" signal bandwidth of 500 kHz and a "Q" signal bandwidth of 300 kHz.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Tests with PAL, SECAM and other NTSC subcarrier frequencies were also attempted.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Some of these broadcasts were on UHF (also an experimental technology at the time), while others were carried over the regular VHF network outside of normal broadcasting hours.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In 1964, the BBC launched its BBC2 service on UHF using only a 625-line system, which older sets could not receive.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] For several years BBC1 and ITV transmitted using the 405-line and BBC2 with the 625-line standard; the only way to receive them all was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line, VHF and UHF, receiver.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The introduction of colour on BBC2 in 1967 necessitated an even more complex dual-standard set to receive all three channels with BBC2 in colour.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Over time in 1968 and 1969, the different ITV regional channels and BBC1 switched over to broadcasting on the 625-line as well as the 405-line, a process which once completed meant that only 625-lines were necessary to receive all channels, with dual standard receivers no longer necessary.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In November 1969, BBC1 and ITV started broadcasting in 625-line PAL colour on UHF.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Their programming was now entirely produced using the new 625-line standard, and thus the 405-line broadcasts served only as a rebroadcast in monochrome for people who did not have the newer receivers and who could only receive BBC1 and ITV.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This situation continued up to 3–4 January 1985, with 405-line VHF receivers only being able to pick up BBC1 and ITV regionals, and in monochrome only, while 625-line UHF receivers could also receive BBC2 and Channel 4/S4C in addition to BBC1 and ITV, and in either colour or monochrome.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] One reason for the long switchover period was the difficulty in matching the coverage level of the new UHF 625-line service with the very high level of geographic coverage achieved with the 405-line VHF service.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line transmissions were seen on 4 January 1985 in Scotland; they had been officially shut down one day earlier in the rest of the UK (although they were actually switched off at various points the next day).
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This left only the UHF PAL system in operation in the UK.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The frequencies used by the 405-line system were initially left empty, but were later sold off; they are now used for other purposes, including DAB and trunked PMR commercial two-way radio systems.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Ireland's use of the 405-line system began in 1961 (officially 31st of December 1961), with the launch of Telefís Éireann, but only extended to two main transmitters and their five relays, serving the east and north of the country.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This was because many people in these areas already had 405-line sets for receiving UK broadcasts from Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Telefís Éireann's primary standard was 625-line; it began using this in the summer of 1962, more than two years before the UK had any 625-line channels.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The last 405 line transmitters in the UK and Ireland were shut down in 1985.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line relays, in County Donegal, were turned off in 1982; the main transmitters had been shut down in 1978 to free up frequencies for RTÉ 2, and after then the relays had been fed by standards converters from the local 625-line transmitter.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] For the last five years of RTÉ's 405-line simulcasting, a simple orthicon converter was used, essentially a 405-line camera pointed at a 625-line monitor, as the more expensive system converters that RTÉ had previously used were now inoperable.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system was used in the Rediffusion Television cable television service in Hong Kong, established in 1957, making it both the first British colony and the first predominantly Chinese city to have television.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The service of 405-line system ended in 1973, replaced by 625-line PAL system free-to-air broadcast.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] For a brief time in 1939 there were experimental 405-line transmissions from stations in Montrouge in France and Eindhoven in the Netherlands, Czechoslovakia and Switzerland.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] After the U.S. adopted the NTSC 525-line monochrome standard for commercial broadcasting in 1941, subsequent efforts were made to upgrade the standard so that it could also accommodate a "compatible" colour broadcasting system.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This system was a field-sequential colour system which electronically transmitted a 405 lines, 144 fields per second monochrome picture.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Colour was provided mechanically by means of a synchronized rotating transparent Red-Green-Blue disk, which was placed in front of the receiver screen.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Regular broadcast channels were used to transmit the 405-line system signals, but the millions of existing NTSC 525-line television receivers could only correctly process the audio portion of these transmissions, so unless these sets were modified they would only display a jumbled picture.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] CBS aired a variety show special entitled *Premiere* on 25 June 1951 to officially launch commercial 405-line colour broadcasting, but just four months later CBS ended its colour broadcasts.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] CBS's efforts were hindered from the beginning by a widespread lack of acceptance, and the ultimate setback came at the end of the year when the U.S. government temporarily banned the manufacture of colour televisions, ostensibly to conserve resources during the Korean War.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In 1953, the FCC rescinded its approval of the CBS 405-line colour system.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In its place it approved a newly improved and now satisfactory second NTSC 525-line standard which had been developed by RCA.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] It provided for colour broadcasting yet remained compatible with existing 525-line monochrome sets.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] 405-line is System A in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The audio uses amplitude modulation rather than the frequency modulation in use on modern analogue systems.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In addition, the system was broadcast in an aspect ratio of 5:4 until 3 April 1950, when it changed to the more common 4:3 format.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] All System A transmitters used vestigial sideband transmission, with the single exception of Alexandra Palace in London, which closed down in 1957 when it was replaced by Crystal Palace.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Secondly, the smoothing (filtering) of power supply circuits in early TV receivers was rather poor, and ripple superimposed on the DC could cause visual interference.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] However, the main problem was the susceptibility of the electron beam in the CRT being deflected by stray magnetic fields from nearby transformers or motors.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] If the picture was locked to the mains frequency, this interference would at least be static on the screen and thus relatively unnoticeable.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The very earliest TV sets used a mains transformer; care had to be taken in design to prevent the transformer's stray magnetic field from disturbing the electron beam in the CRT.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] An interlaced system requires accurate positioning of scanning lines so the horizontal and vertical timebase must be in a precise ratio.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This is done by passing the one through a series of electronic divider circuits to produce the other.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Therefore, there has to be a straightforward mathematical relationship between the line and field frequencies, the latter being derived by dividing down from the former.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The technology constraints of the 1930s meant that this division process could only be done using small integers, preferably no greater than 7, for good stability.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The number of lines was odd because of 2:1 interlace.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system used a vertical frequency of 50 Hz (standard AC mains supply frequency in Britain) and a horizontal one of 10,125 Hz (50 × 405 ÷ 2 or, using the frame rate, 25 x 405), with 405 being derived from (3 × 3 × 3 × 3 × 5).
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] A few 405-line videotapes still survive.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] However, the majority of surviving 405-line programmes are in the form of black and white film telerecordings, usually with optical soundtracks.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Occasionally video re-recording would be employed instead, with a 625-line camera pointing at a 405-line monitor.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This preserves the original 50-field interlaced format, but with some geometrical distortions owing to the curvature of the CRT monitors used at the time.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] 405-line programming may be recorded and played on an unmodified VHS or Betamax video recorder, as long as the input to the recorder is baseband rather than RF.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Thus, various modern video recordings of 405-line programming also exist.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Betamax was sometimes preferred for this, as the dropout compensator could be switched off on certain models for use with PCM digital audio decoders.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] When used with vestigial sideband filtering, the total bandwidth of a 405-line TV channel is 5 MHz, significantly less than the 8 MHz required by the 625-line System I, which replaced it in Britain.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Systems in other countries used anything between six and fourteen megahertz of bandwidth per channel.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The use of VHF frequencies combined with the narrow vision bandwidth — AM signals (at VHF low band frequencies) are less affected by noise as bandwidth is reduced — meant that 405-line signals could be received well even under marginal conditions.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Therefore, it was possible to cover virtually all of the UK with a relatively small number of transmitting stations.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The use of AM (rather than FM) for sound and the use of positive (rather than negative) video modulation made 405-line signals very prone to audible and visible impulse interference, such as that generated by the ignition systems of vehicles.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Such interference manifested itself as a loud popping on sound and large bright spots on the picture, which viewers found much more noticeable than the dark spots encountered when such interference is encountered on a signal using negative video modulation.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] With positive modulation, interference could easily be of similar amplitude to the sync pulses (which were represented by 0–30% of the transmitter output).
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The early time-base circuits were less able to discriminate between the signals and the picture would break up.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] By contrast, in negative modulation sync, pulses represent peak transmitter output (70–100% output).
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] As a result, impulse interference would cause visual dark spots before it was large enough to affect the synchronisation of the picture.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] If the interference was large enough, the picture was probably unwatchable anyway.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The later introduction of flywheel sync circuits rendered the picture much more stable, but these could not have alleviated some of the problems with positive modulation.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Almost all television systems that succeeded the 405-line system adopted negative modulation for this reason alone.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] First-generation AGC merely detected the average value of the transmitted signal; however, due to the positively modulated carrier, peak power represented peak white – not guaranteed to be present.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Thus for a completely black picture, the AGC circuit would increase the RF gain to restore the average carrier amplitude.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The result was a screen that was not black but mid-grey.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] In fact, the total light output of early TV sets was practically constant regardless of the picture content.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] By the mid-1950s, several manufacturers started to introduce gated-AGC systems to avoid this issue.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] A delayed pulse was derived from the recovered line-sync signal.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This pulse would trigger a gate which would sample the received video signal during the "back porch" which was a guaranteed black-level transmitted between the end of the line-sync pulse and the start of the picture information.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The introduction of negative modulation in later systems simplified the problem because peak carrier power represented sync pulses (which were always guaranteed to be present).
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] A simple peak-detector AGC circuit would detect the amplitude of only the sync pulses, thus measuring the strength of the received signal.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system produced a noticeable 10.125 kHz whistle in many sets, equal to the number of lines per second.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This high-pitched whistle was caused by magnetostriction in the line output transformer.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] This is a common artifact in sets that use a cathode-ray tube.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] While all CRT-based television systems produce such a noise, the higher number of lines per second in later standards produces frequencies (PAL's 15.625 kHz and NTSC's 15.734 kHz) that are at the upper end of the audible spectrum, which not all people are able to hear.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Modern sets using plasma, LCD or OLED display technology are completely free of this effect as they are composed of a million or more individually controllable elements, rather than using a single magnetically deflected beam, so there is no requirement to generate the scanning signal.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The question was raised again from time to time, but a series of tests, conducted during 1952 in cooperation with the British Radio Equipment Manufacturers' Association, confirmed that there was no general need for equalizing pulses.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] On some larger TV screen sizes, the scanned lines were not fat enough to give 100% coverage of the CRT.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] The result was a lined picture with darkness between each horizontal scanned line, reducing picture brightness and contrast.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Larger screen sets often used a spot wobble oscillator, that slightly elongated the scanning spot vertically at high frequency to avoid this line separation effect without reducing horizontal sharpness.
[src:bbc-two/405-line-television-system] Spot wobble was also utilised when making telerecordings of 405-line programmes.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Croft and Lloyd devised the concept as a parody of BBC wartime drama *Secret Army* and initially launched the programme with a pilot on 30 December 1982.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The sitcom was eventually commissioned following the success of the pilot and ran for nine series between 7 September 1984 until its conclusion on 14 December 1992.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Both Lloyd and Croft wrote the scripts for the first six series, while the remainder were handled by Lloyd and Paul Adam.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Much like previous sitcoms created by Croft and Lloyd, the programme employed notable elements such as memorable catchphrases and ending credits, cultural clichés, physical humour and visual gags.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] However, *'Allo 'Allo!* differed from these other sitcoms by featuring overarching plot lines rather than simple stand-alone stories, as well as the device of having actors speaking English but with theatrical foreign accents to distinguish each character's nationality.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The sitcom gained strong ratings during its run, with its success leading to it receiving stage show reproductions.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] A special entitled *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!*, aired on 22 March 2007, featured cast members returning to reprise their original roles to perform in a special story after the conclusion of the programme.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] It was accompanied by a documentary about the sitcom, including a highlight reel of episodes and interviews with the cast, production team and fans.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Throughout the programme's broadcast, the sitcom features a number of overarching storylines, with two of these being the most conspicuous.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] René is notably forced into handling the stolen painting under threat of execution, but also due to being indebted to von Strohm for allowing him to fake his death when he is sentenced to execution for unjustified accusations of aiding the Resistance in an act of sabotage.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The painting itself is at one point lost during its concealment, and when it is found a copy is forged.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] It is also sought not only by von Strohm but also Herr Flick who, rather than return it to Berlin, intends to keep it for himself.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The second storyline concerns the involvement of two stranded British airmen, shot down while over Nouvion.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The schemes devised are so bizarre and complicated that they backfire, and usually collide with other schemes concocted by both von Strohm and the Gestapo, invariably leaving all three groups worse off than before.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Other storylines include the efforts to remove von Klinkerhoffen's replacement from power, sabotaging the Germans' plan to invade England, and the subsequent build-up of German concern about an Allied invasion of France following the defeat of Italy.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Like most characters devised for previous sitcoms, the cast for the programme were designed with notable elements to distinguish them throughout the series, be it a catchphrase, gimmick, or saying.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] As each episode builds on previous ones, viewers are often required to have followed the series to the episode they have reached in order to understand the plot.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] As *'Allo 'Allo!* revolved around individual story arcs spread across several episodes, the creators opted for using a comical version of the "As you remember ..." device, commonly used in serials, to act as a recap of events in the current story for the beginning of a new episode.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] This plot device was rare for comedy (including comedy animation), where plots are prominently gag-driven and self-contained, but its use in *'Allo 'Allo!* had a major impact on audiences connecting with the characters.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] It also had considerable benefits for re-runs, as it allowed local TV stations who had reshuffled episodes for their schedule to ensure that their audiences could be aware of the plot events surrounding the story of the episode being broadcast.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The main characters of the series were of four nationalities – French, German, English and Italian.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Lloyd and Croft portrayed this by having non-English characters speak English with the accent of the foreign language, while the English characters spoke in upper-class English accents.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] French, German and Italian characters could understand each other when speaking, but the English characters could not understand the others without someone "translating" for them and vice versa.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The police officer Crabtree was introduced in the second series.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Because the character was an undercover Englishman with a poor grasp of French, the actor, Arthur Bostrom, spoke perfectly when the character spoke in English, but extensively deployed malapropisms to represent when the character was speaking in French.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Bostrom altered certain words in his sentences, substituting different vowels or consonants, changing them into different or nonsensical words, usually laden with innuendo.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] There were sustained attempts by the occupiers to appropriate the *Fallen Madonna*, a local treasure, to provide a nest egg after the war.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The painting was seen and hidden in various guises; it was often secreted, with suggestive possibilities, in a long *knackwurst* sausage.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] An incredible number of forgeries of the *Fallen Madonna* were made, mostly by Lieutenant Gruber and Monsieur Leclerc, which were hidden in *knackwurst* sausages in René's kitchen.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The forgeries were subsequently destroyed in various ways (burned, blown up, minced, eaten by a dog, etc.).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In the end of the *'Allo 'Allo!* series the Fallen Madonna is found long after the war by an elderly René; he and his mistress Yvette quickly elope to Spain with the painting to live happily ever after.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Having previously sold for £4,000 in 2007, the original prop portrait from the series (*The Fallen Madonna with the Big Boobies)* sold for £15,000 at East Bristol Auctions in December 2018.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The picture was purchased by a buyer in Nouvion.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The BBC presented the 6th Marquess of Bath with a specially commissioned copy of the prop that was hung alongside Old Masters in Lord Bath's ancestral home, Longleat.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] After the pilot aired in December 1982, a full-length first series of seven episodes was commissioned and aired from September 1984 onwards.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Series two, three and four followed annually, with six episodes each.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Series five was commissioned with a view to syndicating the show in America.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] As a result, it aired as a single long series of twenty-six episodes between September 1988 and February 1989, with each episode running only twenty-five minutes to allow for commercials.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The attempts to air the show in America failed (although screening rights to the series were later sold to PBS), and so series six had only eight episodes commissioned, which aired from September 1989 onwards.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] On 25 January 1990, Gorden Kaye suffered serious head injuries in a car crash brought on by gale-force winds.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] This delayed the start of the seventh series, which consisted of ten episodes airing from January 1991 onwards.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Series 8 (7 episodes) followed in January 1992, and the ninth and final series of six episodes aired later that year from November onwards.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The first was a 45-minute episode, which followed Series 2 in 1985, and the second was also a 45-minute episode, screened at Christmas 1991, preceding Series 8.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In 1994, two years after the series ended, the BBC broadcast *The Best of 'Allo 'Allo!*, a compilation of clips from the series, linked by new scenes featuring Gorden Kaye and Carmen Silvera, in which René and Edith reminisce about the events of the war.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] On 22 March 2007, a one-off special episode entitled *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!* was filmed in Manchester, and was broadcast on 28 April 2007 at 9 pm on BBC 2.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The storyline involves René writing his memoirs after the war, and the events from the final episode in 1992 have been overlooked.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The new scenes were interspersed with clips from the original series and new interviews.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The actors who reprised their roles were: Gorden Kaye, Vicki Michelle, Sue Hodge, Kirsten Cooke, Arthur Bostrom, Guy Siner, Robin Parkinson, John D.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In addition, Richard Gibson and Sam Kelly are interviewed, although they are not reprising their respective roles.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The only main characters who did not appear in the reunion at all (barring those cases where the actor or actress had died) were Private Helga Geerhart (played by Kim Hartman) and Herr Engelbert von Smallhausen (played by John Louis Mansi).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In 2022, Channel 5 aired a 67-minute special retrospective for their "Comedy Classics" series.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Cast, crew and celebrities discuss and pay tribute to the show.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The documentary features interviews with Guy Siner, Vicki Michelle, Kim Hartman and Sue Hodge, as well as a previously unseen archive interview with Gorden Kaye.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] On 10 March 2008, ProSieben Sat.1 Media bought the rights to broadcast the series for the first time in Germany, which was broadcast on Sat.1 Comedy beginning on 15 February 2010.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In the meantime, the series was also broadcast on German free TV on Comedy Central Germany .
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Many storylines for *'Allo 'Allo* also derive directly from episodes of *Secret Army*, such as the valuable paintings and the accompanying forgeries, which both the Germans and the Resistance are seeking to obtain in the *Secret Army* second series episode "Weekend".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Some actors from *Secret Army* also appear in *''Allo 'Allo!*: Richard Marner, Guy Siner, John D.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Collins, Hilary Minster, David Beckett and Louis Sheldon.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Inspiration was also drawn from patriotic black-and-white British melodramas of the 1940s.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The French village setting is reminiscent of 1972's *Clochemerle*, whilst René's intermediary role between the Germans and the Resistance reflects a comic version of Rick from *Casablanca* (as well as directly matching the proprietor of the café in *Secret Army*).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Having a café-cabaret in the plot, music was often performed on the show.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] This usually took place with Madame Edith singing, and either Lt.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Gruber or Leclerc at the piano, played (out of vision) by Roy Moore.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Occasionally, characters could also be seen whistling or humming tunes at certain points.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] David Croft and Roy Moore composed the theme tune performed at the start and end of each episode.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] It features a French-style melody performed on an accordion, accompanied by a string quartet and other instruments, in the **3** **4** (waltz) time signature.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Carmen Silvera sang the full song and it was released on LP in the 1980s.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The café cabaret music usually took the form of 1930s film and show tunes – reminiscent of the way period songs were also used in *Secret Army*.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Most popular was "Louise" from the film *Innocents of Paris* (1929), which featured a number of times and was even sung in the "broken-French" language of Crabtree, who pronounced the title "Loo-woes".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Gruber sang a number such as "Can't Help Lovin' Dat Man" from *Show Boat* or "(I Got a Woman Crazy for Me) She's Funny That Way" by Neil Monet and Richard A.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] He gazed at René in a slightly lustful manner, replacing lyrics such as "woman" and "she" with "boy" and "he".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] He caused a particular sensation with his straight version of Noël Coward's "Mad About the Boy".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Helga also sometimes stripped to a rather raunchy version (arranged by Roy Moore) of the latter tune.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Captain Bertorelli could be seen singing "'O Sole Mio (It's Now or Never)"; and the British airmen in a prisoner of war camp could be seen singing "Hitler Has Only Got One Ball".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In 1986, Gorden Kaye and Vicki Michelle released a version of the hit song "Je t'aime... moi non plus".
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The characters of Yvette and René could be heard talking and canoodling in a comic manner whilst the familiar musical "Je t'aime..."' melody played in the background.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The song got to number fifty-seven in the UK Singles Chart.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In 1985, Gorden Kaye and Carmen Silvera appeared in the Royal Variety Performance in character as René and Edith, and sang "I Remember It Well" from *Gigi*.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The show gave rise to a successful touring stage-show featuring most of the TV cast.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] This ran from 1986 to 1992, and included three London stage runs as well as international tours.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In January 1990, Gorden Kaye suffered serious head injuries in a car accident.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] As a result, his understudy, John Larson, played the part in a London Palladium production.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Kaye had a dent in his forehead for the rest of his life from a piece of wood that smashed through the car window.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] He wanted to end the television show after his accident, but was persuaded by Jeremy Lloyd to continue.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In Australia Gorden Kaye's part was played by Australian comedian/impressionist Max Gillies (later, Gorden Kaye repaid the favour when he took over Max Gillies' role in another play in Australia, when Max Gillies was unable to take part).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The show was last performed for a summer season at Bournemouth's Pier Theatre in 1996.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In 2007 Gorden Kaye, Sue Hodge and Guy Siner reprised their roles in a production of the stage show in Brisbane, Australia.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] They were joined by Steven Tandy as Colonel von Strohm and Jason Gann as Herr Flick.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] A new touring show, based on the 1992 tour written by David Croft and Jeremy Lloyd, opened at the Gordon Craig Theatre in Stevenage, Hertfordshire on 29 August 2008 before going on a national tour the following year.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Vicki Michelle reprised her role as Yvette Carte-Blanche.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The cast also included Jeffrey Holland playing Rene Artois and his wife Judy Buxton playing Michelle Dubois.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Other cast members included Robin Sebastian as Gruber, James Rossman as Herr Flick, Nell Jerram as Private Helga Geerhart and Claire Andreadis as Mimi Labonq.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The theatrical version is also frequently performed by amateur theatre companies in the UK and elsewhere.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] A sequel stage show, 'Allo 'Allo 2 – The Camembert Caper, written by David Lovesy, David Pibworth and Steve Clark, adapted from the TV series and approved by the Croft and Lloyd estates was published by Concord Theatricals in September 2023.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] This is also available for theatre groups to perform worldwide.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Exterior shooting took place in Norfolk, much of it at Lynford Hall.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Between 1982 and 1987, and from 1989 to 1992, all interior scenes were filmed in front of a studio audience at the BBC Television Centre studios in London.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] For the fifth series, recorded from December 1987 to August 1988, production moved to BBC Elstree Centre in Studio D.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] With hopes for a US syndication deal, the BBC planned to make 26 new episodes of the sitcom; hence, a bigger space was needed for the production.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Even though the US syndication deal did not go ahead as planned, production remained at BBC Elstree Centre for the remainder of the fifth series.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] With more space available, the outside set of Café Rene became a semi-permanent structure in the former ATV Garage building.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The exact location supposed to be depicted in the show was kept vague.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The town of Nouvion does exist, and it is near Abbeville, which was referenced in the show on several occasions.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Road signs used as props in outdoor scenes of the show include signs for Caen, Orbec, Falaise, Livarot, and Pont l'Eveque — all consistent with a location in the department of Calvados, some 200 km to the west of the real Nouvion.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In Australia, Roadshow Entertainment, under licence from the BBC began releasing the series on DVD in 2006, on a semi-annual basis.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] To date, all series have been released on DVD; only *The Return of 'Allo 'Allo!* TV special remains to be released.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Universal Playback, under licence from the BBC, began releasing the series on DVD in 2002.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In the UK six boxed sets with series 1–9 have been released, as well as a complete boxed set.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The original UK releases have episode titles superimposed over the openings of the episodes (series 1–4).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The 2013 re-release of the complete series boxed set omits the majority, but not all of these superimposed titles.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The American releases have no on-screen episode titles, reflecting the way that the shows were originally transmitted.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] In January 2004, BBC Worldwide began releasing the show itself on DVD in North America, distributed by Warner Bros., beginning with Series 1.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] The releases continued on a somewhat irregular basis (approximately twice-yearly).
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] A video game adaptation named *'Allo 'Allo!
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] Cartoon Fun* was released for the Amiga in 1993 by Alternative Software.
[src:bbc-two/allo-allo] It is a platform game where players control René.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Like the BBC's other domestic TV and radio channels, it is funded by the television licence, and is therefore free of commercial advertising.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It is a comparatively well-funded public-service channel, regularly attaining a much higher audience share than most public-service channels worldwide.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Originally styled **BBC2**, it was the third British television station to be launched (starting on 21 April 1964), and from 1 July 1967, Europe's first television channel to broadcast regularly in colour.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It was envisaged as a home for less mainstream and more ambitious programming, and while this tendency has continued to date, most special-interest programmes of a kind previously broadcast on BBC Two, for example the BBC Proms, now tend to appear on BBC Four instead.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] British television at the time of BBC2's launch consisted of two channels: the BBC Television Service and the ITV network made up of smaller regional companies.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Both channels had existed in a state of competition since ITV's launch in 1955, and both had aimed for a populist approach in response.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The 1962 Pilkington Report on the future of broadcasting noticed this, and that ITV lacked any culturally relevant programming.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It therefore decided that Britain's third television station should be awarded to the BBC.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Prior to its launch, the new BBC2 was promoted on the BBC Television Service: the soon-to-be-renamed BBC1.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The animated adverts featured the campaign mascots "Hullabaloo", a mother kangaroo, and "Custard", her joey.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Prior to, and several years after, the channel's formal launch, the channel broadcast "Trade Test Transmissions", short films made externally by companies such as Shell and BP, which served to enable engineers to test reception, but became cult viewing.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel was scheduled to begin at 19:20 on 20 April 1964, showing an evening of light entertainment, starting with the comedy show *The Alberts*, a performance from Soviet comedian Arkady Raikin, and a production of Cole Porter's *Kiss Me, Kate*, culminating with a fireworks display.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] However, at around 18:45 a huge power failure, originating from a fire at Battersea Power Station, caused Television Centre, and indeed much of west London, to lose all power.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC1 was able to continue broadcasting via its facilities at Alexandra Palace, but all attempts to show the scheduled programmes on the new channel failed.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Associated-Rediffusion, the London weekday ITV franchise-holder, offered to transmit on the BBC's behalf, but their gesture was rejected.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] At 22:00 programming was officially postponed until the following morning.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] As the BBC's news centre at Alexandra Palace was unaffected, they did in fact broadcast brief bulletins on BBC2 that evening, beginning with an announcement by the newsreader Gerald Priestland at around 19:25.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] There was believed to be no recording made of this bulletin, but a videotape was discovered in early 2003.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] By 11:00 on 21 April 1964, power had been restored to the studios and programming began, thus making *Play School* the first programme to be shown officially on the channel.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The launch schedule, postponed from the night before, was then shown that evening, albeit with minor changes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In reference to the power cut, the transmission opened with a shot of a lit candle which was then sarcastically blown out by presenter Denis Tuohy.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] To establish the new channel's identity and draw viewers to it, the BBC decided that a widely promoted, lavish series would be essential in its earliest days.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The production chosen was *The Forsyte Saga* (1967), a no-expense-spared adaptation of the novels by John Galsworthy, featuring well-established actors Kenneth More and Eric Porter.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Critically for the future of the fledgling channel, the BBC's gamble was hugely successful, with an average of six million viewers per episode: a feat made more prominent by the fact that only 9 million were able to receive the channel at the time.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] By 1972, 90% of the UK now received the channel.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 1974, BBC2's widely acclaimed singer-songwriter series, *In Concert*, was lauded by *The Guardian* as the only British music television programme that "produced television ideas".
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Unlike BBC1 and ITV, BBC2 was broadcast only on the 625-line UHF system, so was not available to viewers still using sets only capable of receiving the 405-line VHF system.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] This created a market for dual standard receivers which could switch between the two systems.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Set manufacturers increased production of UHF sets in anticipation of a large market demand for the new BBC2, but the market did not materialise.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The early technical problems, which included being unable to transmit US-recorded videotapes due to a lack of system conversion from the US NTSC system, were resolved by a committee headed by James Redmond, although this problem was not unique to BBC2.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 1 July 1967, during the Wimbledon Championships, BBC2 became the first channel in Europe to begin regular broadcasts in colour, using the PAL system.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The thirteen-part series *Civilisation* (1969) was created as a celebration of two millennia of western art and culture to showpiece the new colour technology.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC1 and ITV later joined BBC2 on 625-line UHF band but continued to simulcast on 405-line VHF until 1985.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC1 and ITV simultaneously introduced PAL colour on UHF on 15 November 1969, although they both had broadcast some programmes in colour "unofficially" since September 1969.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 1979, the station's adoption of the first computer-generated channel identification (ident) in Britain, with its use of the double striped, orange '2' logo, heralded the start of computer-generated logos.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The ident, created in-house by BBC engineers, lasted until March 1986.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] As the switch to digital-only terrestrial transmission progressed, BBC Two was (in each region in turn) the first analogue TV channel to be replaced with the BBC multiplex, at first four, then two weeks ahead of the other four channels.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] This was required for those relay transmitters that had no current Freeview service giving viewers time to purchase the equipment unless they had already selected a satellite or cable service.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The last region for BBC Two to end on analogue terrestrial television was Northern Ireland on 10 October 2012.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] At the 2012 Edinburgh International Television Festival, BBC Two was named "Terrestrial Channel of the Year".
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] A high-definition simulcast of BBC Two began broadcasting on 26 March 2013, replacing the standalone BBC HD channel.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] As of 29 November 2018, there are three variations of BBC Two HD (Wales, Northern Ireland, and England).
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Adam Barker served as Acting Controller of the channel after Janice Hadlow left the channel in March 2014 and until Kim Shillinglaw began as the new permanent occupant of the post.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] From 2013, the Controller of BBC Two was given the expanded title Controller of BBC Two and BBC Four, with ultimate oversight of the BBC Four service added to their duties (a BBC Four "Channel Editor", reporting up to this Controller, was allocated day-to-day operational control of Four).
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel forms part of the BBC Television executive group and is answerable to the head of that department, and to the BBC Board.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 20 January 2016, Kim Shillinglaw announced that she had decided to leave the BBC as the Controller of BBC Two & BBC Four; as a result of the reorganisation, the posts of Controller of BBC Two and BBC Four were closed.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Patrick Holland became Channel Controller of BBC Two in March 2017, following his earlier appointment as Channel Editor in July 2016.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2020, it was announced that BBC channels would no longer have individual controllers, with leadership moving to a genre-based structure.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Patrick Holland moved into a new role as Director of Factual.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two's historical scope was arts, culture, some comedy and drama, and appealing to audiences not already served by BBC One or ITV.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel's "highbrow" profile is also in part attributable to a long history of demanding documentaries of all types, beginning with *Civilisation* and *The Ascent of Man* in the 1960s.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Like the early Channel 4, BBC Two also established for itself a reputation as a champion of independent and international cinema, under the *Screen 2* brand.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel has sometimes been judged, increasingly in more recent years, to have moved away from this original role and closer to the mainstream.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Since the launch of the digital-only BBC Four, the BBC has been accused in particular of shifting its more highbrow output to the new channel, which, until the end of the UK's digital TV switchover in October 2012, a minority (7.5% in the final quarter of 2010) of viewers did not receive.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Four's remit is very similar to the earlier remit of BBC2, and contains many documentaries and arts programmes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It has been perceived by some that this strategy is to allow BBC Two to show more popular programmes and to secure higher ratings.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Since 2004 there have been some signs of an attempt to return closer to parts of BBC Two's earlier output with the arts strand *The Culture Show*.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Its most popular programme prior to its 2020 move to BBC One was motoring magazine *Top Gear*.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Much of BBC Two's output has previously or subsequently been shown on other channels.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Some of these programmes are repeats of popular or flagship programmes from BBC Four in a late-night strand, originally called *BBC Four on Two* but now unbranded.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Other programmes are moved to the channel as a result of their success on BBC Three or Four, so that subsequent series are well received.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] An example of this is the BBC Three series *Torchwood*, which was transferred to the channel following the success of the first series.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two is also used as a testing ground for programmes prior to their moving to the flagship BBC One: such examples include *Have I Got News for You* and popular comedies *Absolutely Fabulous* and *Miranda*, which moved to BBC One after success on Two.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Also in August 2014, *The Great British Bake Off* moved to BBC One, due to its success the previous year on BBC Two.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2017, *Bake Off* moved from BBC One to Channel 4.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Another founding part of BBC Two was to provide educational and community programming on the BBC, as part of its public service remit.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC2's Community Programme Unit kept this aspect of the channel's tradition alive into the 1990s in the form of *Video Diaries* and later *Video Nation*.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The Community Programmes Unit was disbanded in 2004.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two has also given various programmes from around the world their first UK broadcasts, and have introduced many more to terrestrial audiences.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In January 2013, BBC Two ceased to show children's programmes and replaced the weekday morning schedule with repeats of the previous BBC One daytime schedule, children's programmes was returned in 2017 and 2022 in Saturday morning.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It also began showing *Sign Zone* in the early hours; prior to 2013, this had been broadcast by BBC One.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] This was the only channel that broadcast Sign Zone in the early hours until the relaunch of BBC Three as a television channel in 2022.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] From October 2013, BBC Two has shown classic programmes like *Bergerac*, *Cagney and Lacey*, *The Rockford Files*, *'Allo 'Allo!*, and *Are You Being Served?* on weekday afternoons, with the retro logos from 1970s and 1980s, between the current programmes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In October 2014, *Russell Howard's Good News* and *Backchat* moved to BBC Two from BBC Three.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2014, BBC Two commissioned Britain's first transgender sitcom, *Boy Meets Girl*, which follows the developing relationship between Leo, a 26-year-old man, and Judy, a 40-year-old transgender woman.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] From 7 April 2015, the morning *Sign Zone* was shown before *Victoria Derbyshire* 8:00 am – 9:00 am including *See Hear* on Wednesday morning.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two is also known for broadcasting some news and current affairs programmes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It broadcasts BBC News updates every morning at 9 am, simulcasting the BBC News channel after it stops simulcasting *BBC Breakfast* on BBC1.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] This includes an edition of *BBC Business Today* at 11:30 and *Sportsday* at 11:45, then fifteen minutes of *BBC News Now*, this had previously been between 2006 and 2010 an edition of *World News Today* and 2010–2011 *GMT*.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] At 12:15 pm during the Parliament session, political debate programme *Politics Live* is broadcast on BBC Two.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On Wednesdays, due to the Prime Minister's Questions, the programme is broadcast at the earlier time of 11:15 am.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The programme is not broadcast on Fridays or when Parliament is on a holiday break, so the simulcast of *BBC News Now* continues until 1:00 pm for the *BBC News at One* on BBC One.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] At 10:30 pm, current affairs programme *Newsnight* provides reports and analysis of the stories behind the day's headlines.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two does not broadcast any news and current affairs programming at the weekend, except Sunday's during the football season when BBC One breaks away after the 7:30 am news summary from Breakfast, which continues on BBC Two until 9:00 am.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] From 2017 until 2019, it broadcast the UK selection show for the Eurovision Song Contest, *Eurovision: You Decide*.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel stopped broadcasting the show after the 2019 edition due to the fact that the BBC opted for an internal selection in collaboration with BMG Rights Management.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2020, it was reported that the programme *Victoria Derbyshire* would end, owing to the BBC's £80m cuts.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Since the beginning of the Coronavirus pandemic, Victoria Derbyshire has been presenting the first hour of BBC News, which continues until 13:00.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two is also known for broadcasting some BBC One programmes in a change to the schedules when BBC One broadcasts breaking BBC News reports.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] For example, during the COVID-19 pandemic, BBC One aired press conferences from the UK government about major developments from the pandemic.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] However, on 9 April 2021 – the day of the death of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh – BBC Two and BBC One both simulcast BBC News for the whole day.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The same would happen on both 8 and 19 September 2022, following the death and state funeral respectively of Elizabeth II.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In a 2013 BBC Populus poll, BBC Two had the third-highest per-country TV channel quality rating among viewers surveyed in 14 countries, behind BBC One and Brazil's TV Cultura.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The 1991 idents featured a sans-serif numeral *2* at the centre of an initially art-related scene; however, the idents moved away from this style as the station's style changed.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Although highly praised, this expansive set of idents was ended in November 2001.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The BBC corporate logo was updated within the idents in October 1997, though the idents moved away from the original viridian colour scheme in these latter years.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The subsequent presentation style was introduced on 19 November 2001 and kept the same figure *2*, but in a yellow background and given a personality.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] At the time, BBC Two became the first BBC channel to feature a box logo.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2007, BBC Two debuted the new theme, a "Window on the World", with the *2* numeral providing that view.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Introduced on 18 February 2007, the new look also had the channel adopt a teal-coloured box logo, featuring the BBC logo above the word *TWO*, now in the font Avenir.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In 2014, in honour of the channel's 50th anniversary, some of the 1990s idents were re-introduced and from 2015, BBC Two Northern Ireland opted to use nearly forty idents from the 1991–2001 set.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 27 September 2018, the 1991–2001 idents were retired once again and BBC Two introduced a new set of idents, based on scenes incorporating a curve motif resembling the number 2.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The new branding is designed to reflect BBC Two's "constant evolution, constant eclecticism, [and] constant sense of quality".
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The new idents are produced by various artists and studios, including Aardman Animations, The Mill and others.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The new identity was developed by BBC Creative and Superunion.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two also has regional variations in Wales and Northern Ireland, which occasionally opt out of the national BBC Two feed to air programmes of local interest.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] One of those variations came in November 2001, when BBC Wales introduced a special opt-out service known as BBC 2W.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It aired weekdays from 8:30 pm to 10 pm in the BBC Two Wales channel space on digital television, and carried a separate schedule of Welsh-produced programming in comparison to the analogue BBC Two Wales.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC 2W was discontinued in 2008 due to the transition to digital terrestrial television, with the main BBC Two Wales schedule being carried on Freeview thereafter.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two Scotland operated until February 2019, when it was replaced by the national feed.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Concurrently, a bespoke BBC Scotland channel was launched, which simulcasts the BBC Two schedule with opt-outs for local programming from 7:00 pm to midnight nightly, and occasionally during the afternoon for news and sports programmes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two is available via most major television providers in the United Kingdom.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The Northern Irish version of BBC Two is widely available in the Republic of Ireland on satellite and cable, as well as being received directly in areas bordering Northern Ireland, or in coastal areas from Wales.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The national version of BBC Two is also available on cable and IPTV in the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, Monaco and Liechtenstein.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The channel is registered to broadcast within the European Union/EEA through the Luxembourgish Broadcasting Regulator – ALIA.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In its early years, reception in Ireland was limited, causing RTÉ to pick up, by arrangement with the copyright holders, selected programmes aired on the channel before BBC One aired them.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 27 March 2013, it began being carried by British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS) to members of HM Forces and their families around the world, replacing the BFBS 2 TV channel, which already carried a selection of BBC Two programmes.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] It shares a channel with CBBC, which broadcasts from early morning until the early evening.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] All feeds of BBC Two in both SD and HD are broadcast unencrypted on the Astra 2E and 2G satellites, allowing viewing across Belgium, the Netherlands, the Republic of Ireland and parts of France, Germany and Spain.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The BBC announced in May 2008 that it had achieved its aim for all programming to have subtitles for viewers with hearing difficulties.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] These are available on the BBC Red Button, and until 23 October 2012, via the Ceefax teletext service.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The BBC also offers audio description on some popular programmes for visually impaired-viewers as well as British sign language interpretation on some of its programmes for deaf and hard-of-hearing viewers.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] The percentage of the BBC's total television output with audio description available is 10%, having been increased from 8% in 2008.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Originally, programmes from BBC Two were shown in high definition on the dedicated BBC HD channel, alongside programmes from BBC Three and BBC Four, as well as some select series from CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] However, in plans outlined by the director general Mark Thompson on 6 October 2011, BBC HD would close to be replaced by *BBC Two HD*, a high-definition simulcast of BBC Two that would work much the same way as BBC One HD.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] This move allowed the corporation to save £2.1 million, used to count towards its budget deficit following the freezing of the licence fee and the additional financial responsibility of addition services.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 19 February 2013, it was announced that BBC Two HD would replace BBC HD from 6:05 am on 26 March 2013.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] Channel numbers for the BBC's HD channels also changed on Sky, to allow BBC One HD and BBC Two HD to sit side-by-side on channels 141, and 142 respectively on the EPG.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 16 July 2013, the BBC indicated that it wants to launch Northern Irish, Scottish and Welsh variations of BBC Two HD; however, this would require the approval of the BBC Trust, with a proposal due to be presented within six months.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 10 December 2013, BBC Two HD was swapped with the SD channel in England on Sky's EPG for HD subscribers.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] On 24 March 2014, BBC Two HD moved to channel 102 on Freesat in England.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] In October 2018, the BBC announced that regional variants of BBC Two HD in Wales and Northern Ireland would launch at the end of November that year on terrestrial, satellite (Wales only) and iPlayer.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two HD in these regions were swapped with the SD channel on Sky's EPG for HD subscribers.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] A Scotland variant was not launched, as BBC Two Scotland was discontinued in February 2019 in favour of the new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:bbc-two/bbc-two] BBC Two Northern Ireland HD later eventually launched on Sky and Freesat on 5 January 2023, with the SD version shutting down on Sky and Freesat on 24 January 2023.
